title> EQ Addict Convicted for Neglect and Murder</span><hr size=1> Father convicted of neglect and abuse lead to son's death. <br>
<br>
Was a man so involved in his favorite online role-playing game that he allowed his infant son to die? For friends, family, and law officers in Tampa, Florida this is a question lacking any real answer. According to the St. Petersburg Times Online, the favorite pastime of one Tony Lamont Bragg, EverQuest, was in fact being played by the guilty father before, during, and after the death of his nine-month-old son, Tony Bragg Jr. <br>
<br>
So engrossed with his session of EverQuest was Bragg that his answer to his boy’s crying was to somehow squeeze him to death, possibly slamming his body into a sturdy doorframe (as later stated by Tony Sr.). Enclosing his son into a closet unattended for more than 24 hours, Bragg later discovered the young child dead with a broken collarbone and punctured heart. <br>
<br>
Faced with the possibility of life in prison, and the belief that the boys death was an unintentional result by the bothered father, Bragg’s lawyers convinced him to plead guilty to the charge of manslaughter which carries a 15 year sentence, and five years parole. <br>
<br>
Just how deeply involved Bragg was with the popular community game of EverQuest still remains a question mark, and it’s involvement in the boys death an even bigger one. And while there’s been no official statement by the survivors of the deceased or the guilty father himself as to how much of a factor, if any, the role-playing game was in the child’s death, EverQuest is doubtful to have been the cause of such a horrible case of abuse. <br>
<br>
Our condolences and sympathies go out for the entire family of the nine-month-old Tony Bragg Jr. <br>
<br>
